(2) As shown in Figure 2, point \( P \) lies on line \( l \) and is to the left of the \( y \)-axis. A line \( PQ \parallel y \)-axis is drawn through \( P \), intersecting line \( m \) at point \( Q \) and the \( x \)-axis at point \( G \). When \( S_{\triangle PCG} = 2S_{\triangle QCG} \), determine the coordinates of points \( P \) and \( Q \);  

(3) The line \( l: y = -x + 6 \) is translated left by 10 units to obtain line \( n \), which intersects the \( x \)-axis at point \( E \). Point \( F \) is the reflection of point \( C \) about the origin. A line \( K \parallel x \)-axis is drawn through \( F \), and point \( M \) lies on line \( K \). If \( \triangle CEM \) is an isosceles triangle with \( CE \) as one of its equal sides, directly write the coordinates of all possible points \( M \) that satisfy the condition.

As shown in the figure, quadrilateral \(ABCD\) is a cyclic quadrilateral of \( \odot O \), with \( AB = AD = 6 \), \( \angle BAD = 90^\circ \), and point \( E \) lying on chord \( AD \) (not coinciding with the endpoints). \( \angle CBE = 45^\circ \), and \( CF \perp AD \), with the foot of the perpendicular \( F \) on the extension of \( AD \). Connect \( CE \). \( \therefore BO = OD \).  

(1) Find the radius of \( \odot O \);  
(2) If \( \angle DCF = \angle ABE \), prove that the line \( CF \) is a tangent to \( \odot O \);  
(3) Through point \( D \), draw \( DG \perp AD \) intersecting \( \odot O \) at \( G \) and \( BC \) at \( H \). Connect \( EH \) and conjecture the relationship between \( \angle AEH \) and \( \angle AEB \). Provide a proof for your conclusion.  

[Note] This problem includes both proof and solution questions. Only the solution questions are to be answered, and the answers to the proof questions should not be returned.

